One verse can correct years of assumptions.

Isaiah 65:17 points forward:

A new heavens and a new earth.

That phrase isn’t a throwaway line.

It’s a preview of the Bible’s destination.

## The end is not “leaving”
Many popular ideas about the afterlife focus on departure:
- leaving earth
- leaving physical reality
- leaving behind creation

But the biblical storyline points to **renewal**:
- judgment of evil
- healing of what was broken
- restoration of what was intended

The Bible is not trying to get you out of the world.

The Bible is trying to get the world back under God.

## Isaiah is building a bridge
Isaiah does something powerful: it holds together
- the holiness of God (justice)
- the mercy of God (restoration)
- the future of God (new creation)

This is why Isaiah isn’t just “prophecy.”

It’s architecture.

## Why Revelation makes more sense when Isaiah is open
When you read Revelation without the prophets, it can feel like a puzzle.

But when you read Revelation with Isaiah open, you start to see:
- repeated imagery
- repeated promises
- repeated warnings
- repeated hopes

Isaiah is one of the major roads that leads to the final picture.

## The practical implication: live like restoration is real
If the future is restored creation, then present obedience matters.

You don’t obey to earn love.

You obey because you believe the King is real, and the Kingdom is coming.

That belief shapes:
- what you tolerate
- what you build
- what you refuse
- what you protect
- what you pass to your children

